# Cursor Rules for Baby Linktree Project

## Typography Guidelines

### Use Arbor Design System Typography Classes

**ALWAYS** prefer arbor typography tokens over individual Tailwind utility classes for typography.

#### Available Arbor Typography Classes:

**Title Classes:**

- `text-title-xl` - 36px, bold, -0.54px tracking, 40px line-height
- `text-title-lg` - 30px, bold, -0.45px tracking, 36px line-height
- `text-title-md` - 24px, bold, -0.36px tracking, 28px line-height
- `text-title-sm` - 20px, bold, -0.2px tracking, 24px line-height

**Body Classes:**

- `text-body-lg` - 18px, normal, 0.09px tracking, 24px line-height
- `text-body-lg-emph` - 18px, medium, 0.09px tracking, 24px line-height
- `text-body-base` - 16px, normal, 0.16px tracking, 20px line-height
- `text-body-base-emph` - 16px, medium, 0.16px tracking, 20px line-height
- `text-body-sm` - 14px, normal, 0.21px tracking, 20px line-height
- `text-body-sm-emph` - 14px, medium, 0.21px tracking, 20px line-height
- `text-body-xs` - 12px, normal, 0.21px tracking, 16px line-height
- `text-body-xs-emph` - 12px, medium, 0.21px tracking, 16px line-height
- `text-body-xxs` - 10px, normal, 0.2px tracking, 16px line-height
- `text-body-xxs-emph` - 10px, medium, 0.2px tracking, 12px line-height

#### Typography Replacement Rules:

**NEVER use these combinations - replace with arbor tokens:**

❌ **Don't use:**

```css
font-medium text-[14px] leading-[20px] tracking-[0.175px]
font-normal text-[14px] leading-[20px] tracking-[0.21px]
font-medium text-[16px] leading-[20px] tracking-[0.16px]
font-normal text-[16px] leading-[20px] tracking-[0.16px]
font-medium text-[18px] leading-[24px] tracking-[0.09px]
font-normal text-[18px] leading-[24px] tracking-[0.09px]
```

✅ **Use instead:**

```css
text-body-sm-emph
text-body-sm
text-body-base-emph
text-body-base
text-body-lg-emph
text-body-lg
```

#### Implementation Guidelines:

1. **When creating new components:** Always use arbor typography classes from the start
2. **When editing existing components:** Replace individual typography utilities with arbor tokens
3. **Color classes:** Keep separate - arbor tokens only handle font properties (size, weight, line-height, letter-spacing)
4. **Other utilities:** Keep layout, spacing, and other non-typography utilities as-is
5. **Use `clsx` not `cn` for typography:** The `cn()` helper uses `tailwind-merge` which strips custom `text-body-*` classes — use `clsx()` directly when applying Arbor typography tokens

#### Example Transformations:

```tsx
// Before
<div className="font-medium text-[14px] leading-[20px] tracking-[0.175px] text-gray-600">
  Title Text
</div>

// After
<div className="text-body-sm-emph text-secondary">
  Title Text
</div>
```

```tsx
// Before
<p className="font-normal text-[16px] leading-[20px] tracking-[0.16px] text-gray-600">
  Body text content
</p>

// After
<p className="text-body-base text-secondary">
  Body text content
</p>
```

## Color Guidelines

### Use Arbor Design System Color Classes

**ALWAYS** prefer arbor semantic color tokens over individual Tailwind color utilities for colors.

#### Available Arbor Color Categories:

**Semantic Background Colors:**

- `bg-primary` - Primary background (light/dark adaptive)
- `bg-secondary` - Secondary background
- `bg-tertiary` - Tertiary background
- `bg-quaternary` - Quaternary background
- `bg-elevated` - Elevated surfaces (modals, cards)
- `bg-inverse` - Inverse background
- `bg-btnPrimary` - Primary button background
- `bg-accent` - Accent background
- `bg-danger` / `bg-dangerSubtle` - Error/danger backgrounds
- `bg-success` / `bg-successSubtle` - Success backgrounds
- `bg-warning` / `bg-warningSubtle` - Warning backgrounds
- `bg-education` / `bg-educationSubtle` - Educational backgrounds

**Semantic Text Colors:**

- `text-primary` - Primary text (highest contrast)
- `text-secondary` - Secondary text (medium contrast)
- `text-tertiary` - Tertiary text (lower contrast)
- `text-quaternary` - Quaternary text (lowest contrast)
- `text-accent` - Accent text
- `text-on-accent` - Text on accent backgrounds
- `text-danger` / `text-dangerOnDanger` - Error/danger text
- `text-success` / `text-successOnSuccess` - Success text
- `text-warning` / `text-warningOnWarning` - Warning text
- `text-education` / `text-educationOnEducation` - Educational text
- `text-on-inverse-primary` / `text-on-inverse-secondary` - Text on inverse backgrounds

**Semantic Border Colors:**

- `border-primary` - Primary borders
- `border-secondary` - Secondary borders
- `border-tertiary` - Tertiary borders
- `border-accent` - Accent borders
- `border-education` - Educational borders
- `border-error` - Error borders
- `border-success` - Success borders
- `border-warning` - Warning borders

**Palette Colors (when semantic colors don't fit):**

- `bg-neutral-{50-950}` / `text-neutral-{50-950}` - Neutral grays
- `bg-accent-{50-950}` / `text-accent-{50-950}` - Accent purple palette
- `bg-red-{50-950}` / `text-red-{50-950}` - Red palette
- `bg-green-{50-950}` / `text-green-{50-950}` - Green palette
- `bg-blue-{50-950}` / `text-blue-{50-950}` - Blue palette
- `bg-yellow-{50-950}` / `text-yellow-{50-950}` - Yellow palette

**Brand Colors (for specific brand usage):**

- `bg-brand-{color}` / `text-brand-{color}` - Brand palette colors
- Available: apple, canopy, chartreuse, currant, dahlia, felt, forest, goldenrod, heather, hydrangea, iris, lavender, lichen, moss, orchid, pansy, poppy, root, rose, shade, sky, slate, chalk, charcoal, concrete, marble, pebble, sand, stone

#### Color Replacement Rules:

**NEVER use these combinations - replace with arbor tokens:**

❌ **Don't use:**

```css
text-gray-600
text-gray-500
text-gray-400
text-slate-700
text-slate-600
bg-gray-50
bg-gray-100
bg-gray-200
bg-white
bg-black
text-blue-600
text-red-500
text-green-600
border-gray-200
border-gray-300
```

✅ **Use instead:**

```css
text-secondary
text-tertiary
text-quaternary
text-primary
text-secondary
bg-primary
bg-secondary
bg-tertiary
bg-elevated
bg-inverse
text-blue-600 (if no semantic equivalent)
text-danger
text-success
border-secondary
border-primary
```

#### Implementation Guidelines:

1. **Semantic First:** Always prefer semantic colors (`text-primary`, `bg-primary`) over palette colors
2. **When creating new components:** Use arbor color classes from the start
3. **When editing existing components:** Replace individual color utilities with arbor tokens
4. **Palette colors:** Only use when semantic colors don't provide the right meaning
5. **Brand colors:** Only use for brand-specific elements, not general UI
6. **Dark mode:** Arbor colors automatically adapt to dark mode via CSS variables

#### Example Transformations:

```tsx
// Before
<div className="bg-white text-gray-900 border-gray-200">
  <h2 className="text-gray-800">Title</h2>
  <p className="text-gray-600">Description text</p>
  <button className="bg-blue-600 text-white">Action</button>
</div>

// After
<div className="bg-primary text-primary border-primary">
  <h2 className="text-primary">Title</h2>
  <p className="text-secondary">Description text</p>
  <button className="bg-accent text-on-accent">Action</button>
</div>
```

```tsx
// Before
<div className="text-red-500 bg-red-50">
  Error message
</div>

// After
<div className="text-danger bg-dangerSubtle">
  Error message
</div>
```

```tsx
// Before
<input className="border-gray-300 focus:border-blue-500" />

// After
<input className="border-secondary focus:border-accent" />
```

## Shadow Guidelines

### Use Arbor Design System Shadow Elevation Classes

**ALWAYS** prefer arbor shadow elevation tokens over hardcoded shadow values.

#### Available Arbor Shadow Elevation Classes:

- `shadow-elevation-100` - Subtle shadow for buttons, small interactive elements
- `shadow-elevation-200` - Medium shadow for panels, cards, dropdowns
- `shadow-elevation-300` - Prominent shadow for floating elements like compose bars
- `shadow-elevation-400` - Heavy shadow for modals, popovers, overlays

#### Shadow Replacement Rules:

**NEVER use these combinations - replace with arbor tokens:**

❌ **Don't use:**

```css
shadow-sm
shadow-md
shadow-lg
shadow-xl
shadow-2xl
shadow-[0px_4px_16px_rgba(0,0,0,0.08)]
shadow-[0_1px_2px_0_rgb(0_0_0/0.05)]
```

✅ **Use instead:**

```css
shadow-elevation-100
shadow-elevation-200
shadow-elevation-300
shadow-elevation-400
```

#### Implementation Guidelines:

1. **When creating new components:** Always use arbor shadow elevation classes from the start
2. **When editing existing components:** Replace individual shadow utilities with arbor tokens
3. **Choose elevation based on visual hierarchy:** Higher numbers = more prominent elements
4. **Consistency:** Use the same elevation level for similar UI patterns across the app

#### Example Transformations:

```tsx
// Before
<div className="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md">
  Card content
</div>

// After
<div className="bg-elevated rounded-lg shadow-elevation-200">
  Card content
</div>
```

```tsx
// Before
<button className="bg-white rounded-full shadow-sm">
  <IconComponent />
</button>

// After
<button className="bg-elevated rounded-full shadow-elevation-100">
  <IconComponent />
</button>
```

```tsx
// Before
<div className="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-[0px_0px_0px_1px_rgba(0,0,0,0.04),0px_4px_16px_0px_rgba(0,0,0,0.08)]">
  Compose bar
</div>

// After
<div className="bg-elevated rounded-xl shadow-elevation-300">
  Compose bar
</div>
```

## Design System Integration

This project uses:

- **@linktr.ee/arbor** - Design system components and tokens
- **@linktr.ee/design-tokens** - Color and spacing tokens
- **Tailwind CSS** - Utility classes for layout, spacing, borders, etc.

### Priority Order:

1. Arbor typography tokens (for font properties)
2. Arbor semantic color tokens (for colors with meaning)
3. Arbor shadow elevation tokens (for shadows)
4. Arbor palette colors (when semantic colors don't fit)
5. Tailwind utilities (for layout, spacing, borders, etc.)

## Code Quality

- Always maintain existing functionality when refactoring typography and colors
- Preserve all non-design-system classes (layout, spacing, etc.)
- Test visual consistency after typography and color changes
- Use semantic HTML elements with appropriate ARIA labels
- Follow the existing code patterns and naming conventions
- Prefer semantic color names over palette colors for better maintainability
- Ensure proper contrast ratios are maintained when using arbor colors
- Test components in both light and dark modes when using arbor tokens

## File Organization

- Components should be in `/components/` directory
- Export components from `/components/index.ts` when appropriate
- Use TypeScript interfaces for component props
- Follow the existing import/export patterns
